---
import Base from '../../../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="Our Teachers" lang="en" description="The teachers of the Szent László Hungarian School.">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <h1 class="page-title">Our Teachers</h1>

    <article class="teacher">
      <img src="/images/tanar-madar-emoke.jpg" alt="Emőke Madár" />
      <div class="prose">
        <h3>Madár Emőke</h3>
        <p>
          I am Emőke Madár, a teacher at the Szent László Hungarian School in
          Vancouver and its principal since May 2022. My family and I moved to
          Vancouver in July 2018; before that I taught in Hungary at a German
          minority-language and dual-language elementary school. As fate would have
          it, I was able to join the teaching at the Szent László Hungarian School
          as early as September 2018. The enthusiasm of the school's volunteer team
          enchanted me from the very beginning. In my work here I can put the
          professional experience I gained at home to very good use, and I keep
          developing my skills, because a weekend Hungarian school requires an
          entirely different approach and material.
        </p>
        <p>
          My goal is to awaken enthusiasm for learning the Hungarian language in as
          many children as possible.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="teacher">
      <div class="prose" style="grid-column: 1 / -1;">
        <h3>Dr. Ungár Júlia</h3>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="teacher">
      <img src="/images/tanar-molnar-katalin.png" alt="Katalin Molnár" />
      <div class="prose">
        <h3>Molnár Katalin</h3>
        <p>
          I am Katalin Molnár. I have been teaching Hungarian at the Szent László
          Hungarian School since 2014, at the suggestion of Ágnes Kalmár. At first
          I had a group of children who spoke Hungarian well; later I taught
          children at various levels depending on their family background. In 2018
          I took part in a four-day methodology course in Budapest organized by the
          KKM–Balassi Institute for teachers who teach Hungarian at weekend schools
          abroad. In 2019 the Methodology Conference taught us how to prepare lesson
          plans, which helped with using the Balassi workbooks — the books published
          in that series support language acquisition and the preservation of
          Hungarian identity for new generations living in the diaspora. Since the
          pandemic I have been teaching online. I graduated from ELTE in Budapest,
          in the Teacher and Kindergarten Education program.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="teacher">
      <img src="/images/tanar-barna-laura.jpg" alt="Laura Barna" />
      <div class="prose">
        <h3>Barna Laura</h3>
        <p>
          I am Laura Barna, a scholarship recipient of the Kőrösi Csoma Sándor
          Program from Budapest. This year I am delighted to join the teachers of
          the Szent László Hungarian School in Vancouver, to make the Hungarian
          language loved and interesting for the children living here. Although I
          do not have a teaching degree, I have been educating and mentoring young
          people within scouting for six years. Scouting is built on "learning by
          doing," and in that spirit I aim to teach playfully, so that the children
          pick up the language while having fun — and along the way get to know
          Hungarian folk customs, holidays, and hungarikums as well. It is a big
          and exciting challenge for me to find the activities and methods that are
          effective and entertaining for the students, whose language levels vary
          widely. Throughout the school year I will do my best to help in the life
          of the school and make sure the children enjoy the classes.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <p><em>The full list of our teachers is being uploaded.</em></p>
  </div>
</Base>
